# demo_variables.yml.example naming conventions

## Section order (mandatory)

1. File header banner
2. Flags (`demo_no_log`, `aap_configuration_secure_logging`)
3. **Vault variable mappings** — map every `vault_*` secret to its plain name
4. AAP connection (`aap_hostname`, `aap_username`, `aap_password`, `aap_validate_certs`,
   `aap_controller_api_prefix`, optional commented `aap_token`)
5. Demo identity (`demo_organization_name`, `demo_organization_description`, `demo_project_name`,
   `demo_label_name`, `demo_inventory_name`, `demo_execution_environment_name`)
6. Git repository configuration block (see `artifact--git-repository.mdc`)
7. Cloud provider blocks — one section per provider, alphabetical (AWS → Azure → GCP)
8. Optional integrations (EDA, SMTP, feature flags)
9. Credential names
10. Setup variables (`playbooks/setup/` inputs)

## Variable prefix conventions

| Prefix | Use for |
|---|---|
| `demo_` | AAP object names, SCM settings, labels, EE name, setup-level operational vars |
| `aap_` | AAP/Controller connection and API settings |
| `azure_` | Azure-specific settings (subscription, tenant, resource group, account names, runbook, schedule) |
| `aws_` | AWS-specific settings (region, SSM, EC2, IAM, maintenance window) |
| `gcp_` | GCP-specific settings |
| `eda_` | EDA Controller connection and rulebook settings |
| `enable_` | Boolean feature flags (`enable_email_notification`, `enable_aws`, `enable_azure`) |
| `<service>_credential_name` | AAP credential object names (e.g. `azure_credential_name`, `aws_credential_name`) |
| Scenario-specific | One prefix per major integration: `proxmox_*`, `f5_*`, `breakglass_*`, `drift_*`, `snapshot_*` |

## Vault mapping section

- Must appear **before** any variable that references a plain name derived from a vault secret.
- Every `vault_*` variable in `vault.yml.example` must have a corresponding mapping line here.
- Format: `plain_name: "{{ vault_plain_name }}"` — no additional logic, no `| default()` filters.
- Do **not** repeat the plain name later in the file with a different value.
- An **incomplete chain is a bug**: `aap_password: "{{ controller_password }}"` requires that
  `controller_password: "{{ vault_controller_password }}"` exists above it.

```yaml
# ============================================================================
# Vault variable mappings
# ============================================================================
# Map vault_ prefixed secrets to the plain names used by roles and playbooks.
# vault.yml must be copied from vault.yml.example and encrypted before use.
controller_username: "{{ vault_controller_username }}"
controller_password: "{{ vault_controller_password }}"
```

## AAP connection block

Always include `aap_controller_api_prefix` for AAP 2.5+ Platform Gateway deployments.

```yaml
aap_hostname: CHANGE_ME
aap_username: "{{ controller_username }}"
aap_password: "{{ controller_password }}"
aap_validate_certs: false
# Controller REST API path prefix when calling through Platform Gateway (AAP 2.5+).
aap_controller_api_prefix: /api/controller/v2
```

Add `aap_token` **only** when the demo explicitly uses token-based (PAT) authentication
instead of username/password. Do **not** add it as a commented-out placeholder if the
demo does not use it — it adds noise without value.

```yaml
# Only when the demo uses PAT auth:
aap_token: "{{ vault_aap_token }}"
```

## Object names that must be unique across artifacts (mandatory)

Several identity variables are used elsewhere in the standard artifact pattern (cleanup
deletes, EE credential resolution) in ways that assume the value is not shared with another
artifact deployed to the same AAP. Reusing a generic placeholder across artifacts is a
recurring source of cross-demo incidents, not a style nit:

| Variable | Why it must be unique | Failure mode if shared |
|---|---|---|
| `demo_organization_name` | `playbooks/aap_cleanup.yml` deletes the Organization by name as its last step; the delete cascades to **every** Project/Inventory/EE/Credential under it | Cleaning up one demo destroys the other demo's AAP objects (see the organization deletion guard in `artifact--casc-playbooks.mdc`, which mitigates but does not replace unique naming) |
| `demo_inventory_name` | Same Organization collision risk, plus ambiguous inventory lookups in constructed-inventory sync tasks | Wrong inventory targeted or sync task resolves the wrong record |
| `demo_azure_inventory_name` / `demo_aws_inventory_name` (or any other child inventory variable) | `ansible.controller.host`, `ansible.controller.group`, and `input_inventories` on `ansible.controller.inventory` all resolve their `inventory:` reference by a name-only Controller API lookup with **no organization filter** (`module.resolve_name_to_id`) | `aap_config.yml` fails with `returned 2 items, expected 1` the moment a second artifact creates a same-named child inventory (e.g. bare `Azure-Resources`) in its own Organization |
| `hub_registry_credential_name` | `ansible.controller.execution_environment`'s `credential:` field resolves via the same kind of name-only Controller API lookup with **no organization filter** (see `artifact--execution-environment.mdc`) | `aap_config.yml` fails with `returned 2 items, expected 1` the moment a second artifact creates a same-named credential in its own Organization |
| Any other `*_credential_name` (e.g. `azure_credential_name`, `aws_credential_name`, `controller_credential_name`) | `job_template`'s and `workflow_job_template`'s `credentials:` list, and `workflow_job_template_node`'s `credentials:`/`execution_environment:` fields, all resolve names the same unscoped way | Same `returned 2 items, expected 1` failure — an audit found generic placeholders like `Azure Service Principal` and `AAP-Controller-Credential` reused verbatim across otherwise-unrelated artifacts; always suffix with the artifact name/slug |

The common root cause above (`ansible.controller.*` modules resolving a bare-name reference
field with no organization filter) is not limited to the rows listed — it applies to **any**
name a CasC object references by string instead of by the object it is defined alongside.
Treat every AAP object name in `demo_variables.yml.example` and `group_vars/all/*.yml` as
artifact-unique by default; only object names that are true singletons controller-wide
(e.g. `credential_type` names for built-in types) are safe to reuse. Run the uniqueness
`grep` below across **all** `*_name` and `*_credential_name` variables, not just the three
historically-bitten ones, when auditing or adding an artifact.

Before finalizing a new artifact's `demo_variables.yml.example`:

- Set every AAP object name to a value **derived from the artifact slug or title** — the
  same convention already used for `demo_project_name` and `demo_execution_environment_name`
  (e.g. `ee-<slug>`). Do not reuse a generic placeholder like `Multicloud Demo`,
  `Demo-Multicloud`, bare `PAH Container Registry`, or bare `Azure-Resources`/`AWS-Resources`
  across artifacts.
- Verify uniqueness against every sibling artifact before shipping. Check the well-known
  identity variables plus **every** `*_name`/`*_credential_name` variable, since new
  variables (child inventories, per-cloud credentials, etc.) are just as exposed:

  ```bash
  grep -rhoE "^[a-z0-9_]+_(name|credential_name):\s*\"?[^\"#{]+" \
    artifacts/demos/*/group_vars/all/demo_variables.yml artifacts/demos/*/group_vars/all/demo_variables.yml.example \
    | sed -E 's/\s+$//' | sort | uniq -d
  ```

  Any `key: value` line printed by that pipeline is reused verbatim across two or more
  artifacts and must be disambiguated. For a quick manual check of just the
  historically-bitten variables:

  ```bash
  grep -rn "demo_organization_name:\|demo_inventory_name:\|demo_azure_inventory_name:\|demo_aws_inventory_name:\|hub_registry_credential_name:" \
    artifacts/demos/*/group_vars/all/demo_variables.yml.example
  ```

  If any value matches an existing artifact's value, rename the new artifact's value —
  never the existing one, unless the two artifacts are an intentional multi-artifact split
  of the same engagement that is meant to share one Organization (rare; document this
  explicitly in both READMEs if so — and note that `hub_registry_credential_name` and any
  child inventory name must stay unique even then, since these name-resolution bugs are not
  related to Organization sharing).

## EDA connection block (when EDA is in scope)

```yaml
eda_hostname: CHANGE_ME
eda_username: "{{ eda_controller_username }}"
eda_password: "{{ eda_controller_password }}"
eda_validate_certs: false
eda_rulebook_name: CHANGE_ME
```

Map `eda_controller_username`/`eda_controller_password` from vault in the mapping section.

## Feature flags and optional cloud slices

Use `enable_<feature>` boolean flags for optional integrations or cloud provider slices:

```yaml
enable_email_notification: false
enable_aws: true
enable_azure: true
```

## Hub / custom EE variables (when a custom execution environment is in scope)

Owned by **`artifact--execution-environment.mdc`** — define these three variables there, not
here, and do not restate them with different values. Placed in the **demo identity** section (5),
immediately after `demo_execution_environment_name`:

```yaml
demo_execution_environment_image: CHANGE_ME/ee-<slug>:latest
hub_registry_credential_name: PAH Container Registry
hub_registry_host: "{{ aap_hostname | regex_replace('^https?://', '') | regex_replace('/$', '') }}"
```

## RBAC-heavy scenarios

Add `demo_team_name` when the demo creates teams or RBAC objects in AAP:

```yaml
demo_team_name: CHANGE_ME
```

## Placeholder conventions

| Situation | Value |
|---|---|
| Operator must supply a unique value | `CHANGE_ME` |
| Operator must supply a unique value (semantic context helpful) | `CHANGE_ME_<SUFFIX>` (e.g. `CHANGE_ME_ROLE_ARN`) |
| SCM URL | `CHANGE_ME_GIT_REPO_URL` |
| Value populated by a setup playbook output | `CHANGE_ME` with a comment naming the playbook |
| Sensible default that can be kept as-is | Actual default value (e.g. `us-east-1`, `main`) |

Use semantic `CHANGE_ME_*` suffixes when multiple CHANGE_ME values in the same block
would be ambiguous (e.g. `CHANGE_ME_ACCOUNT_ID` vs `CHANGE_ME_ROLE_ARN`).

## What does NOT belong here

- Raw secrets — use `vault.yml.example` for passwords, keys, tokens.
- Duplicate definitions of the same variable (second definition silently wins in YAML).
- Computed URLs via Jinja conditionals — see `artifact--git-repository.mdc`.
- Non-secret IDs (subscription ID, tenant ID, resource group) are **not** secrets and must
  live here, not in `vault.yml.example`.
